    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-02T16:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-02T16:00:00-05:00" n="912"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d912">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.4A5/11–344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-03T00:00:00+03:00"
                            >November 3, 1944—midnight</date>.<lb/>[Received November 3—10:55
                        p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4222. The Embassy has received a note from Foreign Office<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d912fn49">For text of Soviet note No. 74 of November 2, 1944, see
                        Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, July 22, 1945, p.
                        130.</note> (regarding Department’s airmail instruction No. 279 of August
                        21)<note n="50" xml:id="d912fn50">See footnote 34, <ref target="#pg_1094">p.
                            1094</ref>.</note> stating in effect: <list>
                        <label>(1)</label>
                        <item>The Soviet Government appreciates the efforts of the American
                            Government directed towards extirpating illegal traffic in opium and
                            towards production and use of opium only for medicinal and scientific
                            purposes;</item>
                        <label>(2)</label>
                        <item>The question of a postwar conference and of the terms which might be
                            included in a convention for restricting the cultivation of poppies is
                            being studied by the competent Soviet authorities at the present
                            time;</item>
                        <label>(3)</label>
                        <item>With reference to proposal that the Soviets issue a declaration
                            concerning the restriction of opium production to the amount
                            indispensable satisfying only medicinal and scientific needs, the
                            existence of a state monopoly both in the field of production and
                            distribution makes the issuance of such a declaration
                            unnecessary.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
